                    <item>
              <title>Documenting and reporting</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/2993</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/2993</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p>A6: An ability to summarise, document, report and reflect on progress</p>
<h2>Check this skill</h2>
<p>By the time students complete a PhD, they should be able to answer &lsquo;Yes&rsquo; to most of these questions.</p>
<ul>
<li>Do you      keep clear, dated records of what you read, when you read it, and what you      thought about it? </li>
<li>Do you      keep accurate notes in Endnote or other referencing software? </li>
<li>Do you      keep a research journal that both summarises information from other      sources (e.g., notes from seminars or discussions) and records your own      ideas and reasoning? </li>
<li>Can you      articulate three things you have learned since you started your PhD? </li>
<li>Do you      keep notes of your supervision meetings? Are the notes complete enough to      allow you to identify the key ideas discussed, any decisions made, and any      actions specified? </li>
<li>Can you      write succinct but clear summaries of your research of varying lengths      (e.g., 50 words, 100 words, 500 words, 1000 words, 10 pages) and for      various audiences (e.g., the public, different specialisms, generalists      within your discipline)? </li>
<li>Do you      collect together and tidy the documentation for each phase or element of      your research as it is completed? </li>
<li>Do you      have a work plan? </li>
<li>Do you      monitor and adjust it regularly? </li>
<li>Do you      regularly review your Training Plan and update it? Can you summarise in      five sentences a seminal paper, a seminar you have recently attended, or a      research conversation you've had? </li>
<li>Can you      identify the three key ideas in a paper or seminar and explain how they      relate to your work? </li>
</ul>
<h2>Evidence of this skill</h2>
<p>These are examples of documents you can collect. Each implies a piece or work, which may be a good way for you to develop this skill.</p>
<ul>
<li>Your probation report / Annual reports. </li>
<li>Progress reports. </li>
<li>Reports and action notes from supervision sessions. </li>
<li>Training plan, updated regularly. </li>
<li>Your Endnote database. </li>
<li>A reflective account of what you have learned in a specific context (e.g. from attending a conference). </li>
<li>An annotated bibliography. </li>
<li>An ongoing research journal or blog.</li>
<li>A personal home page, with links to your key research interests, activities and outputs so far.</li>
</ul>
<p><em>This page is based upon material produced by The Open University&rsquo;s research school to support doctoral students. </em></p>]]></description>
